By <a href="https://www.politico.com/staff/nahal-toosi" rel="author" class="url fn" target="_top">NAHAL TOOSI</a></p>
<p class="timestamp"><time itemprop="datePublished" datetime='2019-12-21 11:02:05'>12/21/2019 11:02 AM EST</time></p>
</footer></footer>
</div>
</div>
<p>President Donald Trump is pulling out all the stops to convince North Korea to return to nuclear talks – delaying military exercises, ambushing efforts to highlight the regime’s human rights abuses and sending a top envoy to the region to reassure jittery allies.</p>
<p>Democrats are calling on Trump to stick to diplomacy and even strive for a limited interim agreement, while lawmakers in both parties want the White House to be more transparent about what it knows about North Korea’s nuclear capabilities. </p><p class="story-full">
<a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/21/trump-north-korea-089107" target="_top">Read More &raquo;</a></p>
