<h1>
<a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/12/robert-gates-north-korea-1317623" target="_top">North Korea won’t give up all its nuclear weapons, former Defense Secretary Gates says</a></h1>
</header>
<footer class="meta">
<footer class="meta">
<div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
<meta itemprop="name" content="Patrick Temple-West" />
<meta itemprop="email" content="ptemple-west@politico.com" />
</div>
<p class="byline">
By <a href="https://www.politico.com/staff/patrick-temple-west" rel="author" class="url fn" target="_top">PATRICK TEMPLE-WEST</a></p>
<p class="timestamp"><time itemprop="datePublished" datetime='2019-05-12 09:22:56'>05/12/2019 09:22 AM EDT</time></p>
</footer></footer>
</div>
 </div>
<p>Former Defense Secretary Robert Gates said North Korea is unlikely to ever give up all its nuclear weapons, and that President Donald Trump was right to walk away from deal with leader Kim Jong-un in February.</p>
<p>In an interview with CBS that taped on May 10, Gates said North Koreans have come to see some modest nuclear capabilities as “essential to their national survival.”</p><p class="story-full">
<a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/12/robert-gates-north-korea-1317623" target="_top">Read More &raquo;</a></p>
</div>
