<h1>
 <a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/05/mike-pompeo-north-korea-missiles-1302506" target="_top">Pompeo bullish on North Korea talks despite weapons launches</a></h1>
</header>
<footer class="meta">
<footer class="meta">
<div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
<meta itemprop="name" content="Quint Forgey" />
<meta itemprop="email" content="qforgey@politico.com" />
</div>
<p class="byline">
By <a href="https://www.politico.com/staff/quint-forgey" rel="author" class="url fn" target="_top">QUINT FORGEY</a></p>
<p class="timestamp"><time itemprop="datePublished" datetime='2019-05-05 10:58:10'>05/05/2019 10:58 AM EDT</time></p>
</footer></footer>
</div>
</div>
<p>Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said Sunday the Trump administration is eager to “get back to the table” for nuclear weapons negotiations with North Korea — one day after leader Kim Jong Un oversaw a barrage of weapons launches from the rogue state’s coast into the sea.</p>
<p>“We still believe that there's an opportunity to get a negotiated outcome where we get fully verified denuclearization. Chairman Kim has repeated that,” Pompeo told host Jonathan Karl on ABC’s “This Week.”</p><p class="story-full">
<a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/05/mike-pompeo-north-korea-missiles-1302506" target="_top">Read More &raquo;</a></p>
